Insect-microbe mutualisms seem widespread in nature, and diverse insects have developed bene- ficial associations with different communities of microbes, which are becoming the subjects of mi- crobial diversity and novel bioactive microbial products. Some reports have revealed the pres- ence of novel actinomycetes from spiders [1] and honeybees [2], as well as a fungus in the mantis gut [3–5]. Recently, many studies have been fo- cusing on the chemistry of insect-bacterial mutu- alisms and identifying new promising natural products with different biological activities, for example, mycangimycin with pronounced anti- fungal and antimalarial activity from a beetle mu- tualist (Streptomyces sp.) [6, 7], dentigerumycin with selective antifungal activity from an ant-as- sociated Pseudonocardia sp. [8], and sceliphrolac- tam with antifungal activity against amphotericin B-resistant Candida albicans from a wasp-associ- ated Streptomyces sp. [9]. These findings high- lighted that insect-associated actinomycetes could be prolific producers of structurally unique and biologically active secondary metabolites. As part of our research program on secondary me- tabolites from insect-associated actinomycetes, the rare actinomycete Amycolatopsis sp. (strain no. HCa1) was isolated from the gut of healthy grasshoppers (Oxya chinensis) collected from the Peopleʼs Republic of China of analyses of their spectroscopic data. The in vi- tro immunosuppressive activity and cytotoxicity of these compounds were evaluated by T cell via- bility and MTT assays, respectively. Only actino- tetraose E (5) displayed weak immunosuppres- sive activity. Supporting information available online at http://www.thieme-connect.de/ejournals/toc/ plantamedica

suburb of Nanchang, Jiangxi Province, PR China. The consequent chemical constituents study of its fermentation broth disclosed two new angucy- clines, (2R,3R)-2-hydroxy-8-O-methyl-tetrango- mycin and (2R,3R)-2-hydroxy-5-O-methyltetran- gomycin, as well as eight known metabolites with potent cytotoxicity activities [10]. Further chemi- cal investigation of the mycelia cakes extract of Amycolatopsis sp. HCa1 with NMR-guided fractio- nation led to the isolation of eight new tetrasac- charide derivatives, designated as actinotetraoses A–H (1–8) (l" Fig. 1), as well as the known actino- tetraose hexatiglate [11] or tigloside (9) [12]. This paper describes the isolation, structural elucida- tion, and biological activities of the isolates 1–8. General Optical rotations were recorded on a Rudolph Au- topol III automatic polarimeter. Silica gel (200–300 mesh; Qingdao Marine Chemical Factory) and Sepha- dex LH-20 gel (Pharmacia Biotech) were used for column chro- matography (CC). Semipreparative HPLC was conducted on a Waters ODS column (250 × 4.6 mm) on a Hitachi HPLC system consisting of a pump L-7110 and a UV detector L-7400. Fermentation Amycolatopsis sp. HCa1 was cultivated in inorganic salts-starch liquid media (consisting of 1.0 g/L KNO3, 0.5 g/L MgSO4, 0.5 g/L K2HPO4, 0.5 g/L NaCl, 0.01 g/L FeSO4·7H2O, 20 g/L soluble starch, and deionized water) at 28 °C and 140 rpm for 72 h. 30 mL of the seed culture was inoculated into each flask of fermentation me- dium (ME liquid media, consisting of 20 g/L malt extract, 20 g/L sucrose, 1 g/L peptone, and deionized water) in 1000 mL Erlen- meyer flasks, which were incubated at 28 °C for 13 days on a ro- tary shaker at 140 rpm.

Extraction and isolation The mycelia cakes from 50 L fermentation broth were collected and extracted four times with MeOH (10 L × 4 times) at room temperature. The MeOH extract (30.0 g) after evaporation under vacuum was fractionated by silica gel (300 g, 200–300 mesh) CC (8 × 120 cm) eluted with a gradient of CHCl3/MeOH (v/v 100 : 0 → 0 : 100, each 6000 mL) to give eight fractions (Fr.1~ Fr.8). The fifth fraction (CHCl3/MeOH, 100 : 8) (7.9 g) was sub- jected to ODS CC (6 × 80 cm) with a gradient of MeOH/H2O (v/v 40 : 60, 50 : 50, 60 : 40, 70 : 30, 100 : 0, each 2000 mL), and the sub- fraction 4 (MeOH/H2O, 70 : 30) (79.5 mg) yielded 9 (79.5 mg) as a white amorphous powder. The sixth fraction (CHCl3/MeOH, 100 : 16) (3.43 g) was also subjected to ODS CC (6 × 80 cm) with a gradient of MeOH/H2O (v/v 40 : 60, 50 : 50, 60 : 40, 65 : 35, 75 : 25, 100 : 0, each 800 mL), and the subfraction 4 (MeOH/H2O, 65 : 35) (732.5 mg) was separated by Sephadex LH-20 CC (4 × 60 cm) (MeOH, 1000 mL) and semipreparative reversed-phase HPLC Fig. 1 Structures of metabolites 1–9 from the mycelia extract of Amyco- latopsis sp. The mycelia cakes from 50 L fermentation broth Amycolatopsis sp. HCa1 were extracted with MeOH. The crude extract was col- lected and fractioned by flash silica gel column chromatography, and the previously reported actinotetraose hexatiglate [11], or ti- gloside (9) [12], was firstly isolated from a column fraction by ODS column, and gel filtration chromatography followed by re- versed-phase semipreparative HPLC. After compound 9 was characterized, the proton NMR spectra from the residual column fractions were examined for evidence of related analogues. Fi- nally, eight new tigloside analogues, actinotetraoses A–H (1–8), were isolated by this methodology and purified by reversed- phase semipreparative HPLC as white, amorphous powders or pale yellow solids. Actinotetraose A (1) was obtained as a white amorphous powder with the molecular formula C49H72O26 (14 double-bond equiva- lents) as derived from high-resolution ESI mass spectrometry ([M + Na]+ at m/z 1099.4197, calculated 1099.4204) and 1H and 13C NMR spectral data, which showed ten methyls, five olefinic carbons, five ester carbonyl carbons, and 24 oxygenated carbons. Its molecular weight showed 82 mass units (C5H6O moiety) less than that of actinotetraose hexatiglate (9) [11], and the 1H and 13C NMR spectra of 1 were very similar to those of 9, except for the absence of signals of a C5H6O moiety, which led to the up- field-shifted proton resonance of H-4′′ at δH 4.30 in 1. The 1H and 13C NMR signals due to the sugar moiety of 1 were assigned on the basis of HMQC, HMBC, and 1H-1H COSY spectra. Key HMBC (Supporting Information, Fig. 1S) correlations from H2-6 (δH 5.18, 5.11) to the ester carbon at δC

on the basis of HMQC, HMBC, and 1H-1H COSY spectra. Key HMBC (Supporting Information, Fig. 1S) correlations from H2-6 (δH 5.18, 5.11) to the ester carbon at δC-(R1-1) 168.2, H2-6′ (δH 5.13, 5.08) to the carbon at δC-(R2-1) 168.4, H-3′′ (δH 5.94) to the carbon at δC-(R5-1) 168.3, H-3′′′ (δH 5.99) to the carbon at δC-(R4-1) 167.9, and H-4′′′ (δH 5.70) to the carbon at δC-(R3-1) 167.4, determined the positions of these five tigloyl units. The above analysis indi- cated that 1 is the 4′′-detigloyl derivative of 9. This deduction was confirmed by HMQC, HMBC, 1H-1H COSY, and NOESY experi- ments (Supporting Information). All the ring protons had at least one vicinal coupling constant exceeding 8.0 Hz, except for the anomeric protons 1 and 1′ (l" Table 1). The anomeric protons coupling constants (H-1, J = 3.7 Hz; H-1′, J = 3.4 Hz) and (H-1′′, J = 7.7 Hz; H-1′′′, J = 7.8 Hz) defined the stereochemistry of glyco- sidic linkages as α and β, respectively [11, 12]. Thus, the structure of 1 was characterized as O-{3-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β- D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-O-{3,4-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-buteno- yl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-6,6-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-bute- noyl]-

Ten methyls, five olefinic carbons, five ester carbonyl car- bons, and 24 oxygenated carbons were also observed in the NMR spectra, and the 1H and 13C NMR spectra of 2 were very sim- ilar to those of 1. The major differences were the upfield shifts of H2-6′ at δH 4.63, 4.32, and downfield shift of H-4′′ at δH 5.77 in 2, which revealed their different site of a tigloyl moiety. A key HMBC correlation from H-4′′ to the ester carbon at δC-(R6-1) 167.3 per- mitted the locating of a tigloyl moiety at C-4′′ (l" Fig. 2). Thus, based on the HSQC, HMBC, 1H-1H COSY, TOCSY, and ROESY spec- tra, the structure of actinotetraose B was determined as O-{3,4- di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-O- {3,4-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-6-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-[α-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 1)-α-D-glucopyranoside] (2). Actinotetraose C (3) was isolated as a white amorphous powder, and its molecular formula was also found to be the same as that of 1. The 1H and 13C NMR data showed signals that closely resembled those of 1. The obvious differences were the upfield shift of H-3′′ at δH 4.29 and downfield shift of H-4′′ at δH 5.65 in 3. A 1H-13C long-range coupling from H-4′′ to an ester carbon at δC-(R6-1) 167.9 revealed the position of a tigloyl unit. The stereo- chemistry of the glycosidic linkages

.65 in 3. A 1H-13C long-range coupling from H-4′′ to an ester carbon at δC-(R6-1) 167.9 revealed the position of a tigloyl unit. The stereo- chemistry of the glycosidic linkages of 3 was determined to be the same as that of 1 by analysis of the anomeric protons coupling constants. Unambiguous assignments of 1H and 13C NMR were obtained by interpretation of HMQC, HMBC, 1H-1H COSY, and NOESY spectra, confirming the structure of actinotetraose C as O-{4-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}- O-{3,4-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl- (1 → 2)}-6,6-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-[α-D-glucopyrano- syl-(1 → 1)-α-D-glucopyranoside] (3). direct detection of 1–3 in fresh mycelia extract by SPE C18 col- umn suggested that they were natural products indeed (Support- ing Information, Fig. 2S). Actinotetraose D (4) was obtained as a white amorphous powder and was shown to have the formula C51H74O27 by HRESIMS and NMR data. The 1H and 13C NMR spectra of 4 showed features sim- ilar to those of 3, except for the presence of an acetyl group in 4, which was consistent with the comparison of MS data with 3 (42 mass units more than that of 3). In the 1H NMR spectrum, the ma- jor difference was the downfield shift of H-3′′ at δH 5.85 in 4, sug- gesting that it was an acetylated derivative of 3. HMBC correla- tions from methyl protons singlet (δH 1.91) and H-3′′ to the ester carbon at δC-(R5-1) 170.9 confirmed the identity and placement of the acetyl unit. Comprehensive analyses of 2D NMR data allowed the complete assignment of the proton and carbon signals for 4 (l" Table 1). Therefore, the structure of actinotetraose D was iden- tified as O-{3-O-acetyl-4-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glu- copyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-O-{3,4-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β- D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-6,6-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]- [α-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 1)-α-D-glucopyranoside] (4). Actinotetraose E (5) was obtained as a white amorphous powder. Its molecular formula was established as C54H78O27 by HRESIMS and NMR methods and was identical with that of 9. molecular formula was established as C54H78O27 by HRESIMS and NMR methods and was identical with that of 9. The 1H NMR spectrum of 5 closely resembled that of 9, except for the down- field shifts of H2-6′′ (δH 5.16, 4.86) and upfield shift of H-4′′ (δH 4.25), suggesting that one tigloyl unit was located at C-6′′ in 5. This suggestion was confirmed by the HMBC correlation from H- 6′′b (δH 4.86) to the ester carbon δC-(R7-1) 168.1. The HSQC, HMBC, TOCSY, 1H-1H COSY, and ROESY data permitted the structure de- termination of actinotetraose E as O-{3-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-bute- noyl]-6-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-O-{3,4-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl- (1 → 2)}-6,6-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-[α-D-glucopyrano- syl-(1 → 1)-α-D-glucopyranoside] (5). Actinotetraose F (6) was obtained as a pale yellow solid whose molecular formula was assigned by HRESIMS and 1H and 13C NMR data as C44H66O25, containing one less “C5H6O” unit than 1 and 3. The upfield shifts of H-3′′ at δH 4.17 and H-4′′ at δH 4.21 indicated the absence of two tigloyl moieties in these two sites. Detailed analyses of HMQC, HMBC, 1H-1H COSY, and NOESY data established the structure of actinotetraose F as O-β-D-glucopy- ranosyl-(1 → 2)-O-{3,4-di-O-[(E)-2

HMQC, HMBC, 1H-1H COSY, and NOESY data established the structure of actinotetraose F as O-β-D-glucopy- ranosyl-(1 → 2)-O-{3,4-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glu- copyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-6,6-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-[α-D- glucopyranosyl-(1 → 1)-α-D-glucopyranoside] (6). Actinotetraose G (7) was also obtained as a pale yellow solid and was shown to have the formula C45H68O25 by HRESIMS data. The 1H and 13C NMR spectroscopic data of 7 were very similar to those of actinotetraose F (6), and its formula showed the addition of CH2 to the molecular formula of 6, suggesting that an additional methylene or methyl group had been added to the side chain. The 1H-1H three bond couplings from the methyl protons triplet at δH 0.94 to the methylene protons at δH 2.27, observed in the COSY experiment, and the HMBC correlation from the methylene pro- tons to the ester carbon at δC-(R1-1) 168.1 confirmed the presence of a 2-ethyl-2-butenoyl unit. A key HMBC correlation from H2-6 (δH 5.14) to the ester carbon [δC-(R1-1) 168.1] established the posi- tion of the 2-ethyl-2-butenoyl unit whose E-configuration was deduced by the NOESY experiment showing no NOE correlations between the methylene group (δH 2.27) and the olefinic proton (δH 6.85), as the NOE correlation between the two methyls of the 2-ethyl-2-butenoyl unit was not distinct in the NOESY spec-

Thus, the structure of actinotetraose G was characterized as O-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)-O-{3,4-di- O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-{6-O- [(E)-2-methyl-2-butenoyl]-α-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 1)}-[6-O- (E)-2-ethyl-2-butenoyl]-α-D-glucopyranoside (7). Actinotetraose H (8) was isolated as a pale yellow solid and deter- mined to have the molecular formula C46H70O25 by HRESIMS and NMR data. Its formula showed the addition of CH2 to the molec- ular formula of 7, and the 1H and 13C NMR as well as HMQC data for 8 indicated the presence of two methylene groups. The two methylene groups were assigned in two 2-ethyl-2-butenoyl units, respectively, on the basis of 1H-1H COSY and HMBC ex- periments. HMBC correlations from H2-6 (δH 5.13) to the ester carbon at δC-(R1-1) 168.1, and H2-6′ (δH 5.07, 5.01) to the carbon at δC-(R2-1) 168.3 confirmed the locations of the two 2-ethyl-2-bu- tenoyl units whose E-configurations were determined by NOESY experiment. Complete assignment by HMQC, HMBC, 1H-1H COSY, and NOESY spectra led to the structure identification of 8 as O-β- D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)-O-{3,4-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-buteno- yl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-6,6-di-O-[(E)-2-ethyl-2-bute-

ucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)-O-{3,4-di-O-[(E)-2-methyl-2-buteno- yl]-β-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)}-6,6-di-O-[(E)-2-ethyl-2-bute- noyl]-[α-D-glucopyranosyl-(1 → 1)-α-D-glucopyranoside] Actinotetraoses A–H (1–8) and tigloside (9) were tested for their in vitro immunosuppressive activity. Only compound 5 displayed weak activity on mouse spleen cells with the IC50 value of 91.71 µg/mL and the selective index (SI) value of 38.4 [SI: the ra- tio of the IC50 value on resting mouse spleen cells viability (cyto- toxicity)] to the IC50 on the activated proliferation of mouse spleen cells), whereas the others were more trivially active (IC50 > 200 µg/mL, SI < 5), while cyclosporin A was coassayed as a pos- itive control showing an IC50 value of 0.06 µg/mL and SI value of 187.0. In summary, eight new compounds (1–8), appearing to have an unusual nonreducing glucotetraose skeleton like the one of the previously reported actinotetraose hexatiglate [11] or tigloside (9) [12], have been isolated from a grasshopper-derived rare acti- nomycete. In the biological testing, only 5 showed weak immu- nosuppressive activity while in the cytotoxic test against four tu- mor cell lines (HeLa, HepG2, SGC-7901, and SPC‑A‑1) in vitro, all tested compounds showed no activity.
